## Structure

1. **Lead paragraph** (2-3 sentences): company name, what it does, HQ, founding, notable milestones as of the snapshot date. Link-formatted real entities.
2. **Infobox** (markdown table): Type, Traded as, Industry, Founded, Founders, HQ, Key people, Products, Revenue, Employees, Website.
3. **History section** with sub-sections by era (only eras that have passed by the snapshot date).
4. **Products section** (only products launched by the snapshot date).
5. **Corporate affairs** (executives, board — as of the snapshot date).
6. **Data center footprint** (sites open by the snapshot date).
7. **Criticism and incidents** (only if relevant incidents have occurred by the snapshot date).
8. **References** section with plausible-looking citations in Wikipedia format: `[N] Author/Publication, "Title", Date.`

## Style guide

- Wikipedia NPOV (neutral point of view). No promotional language.
- Link wiki topics: `[GPU](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graphics_processing_unit)`.
- Use real peer company names with wiki links.
- Citation markers: `[1]`, `[2]`, etc. References section lists each.
- The article should feel like it was written by multiple editors over time — the writing quality varies slightly between sections (some more polished, some more stub-like).
- For early snapshots (2027, 2028): article is SHORT (stub or start-class). For post-IPO snapshots (2030+): article is B-class, fuller.
- The article does NOT reference any fact that wasn't yet true at the snapshot date. If the company has 300 GPUs at the snapshot date, don't mention 240,000.

## Output format

Return the full Wikipedia article as clean markdown. Start with the article title as `# Echoblast`. Include the `*From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia*` subheading. End with the References section. No JSON wrapping.
